Here's a simple JavaScript function using regex to extract a three character code from a filename in the mentioned format:

```javascript
function getThreeCharCode(filename) {
    var pattern = /[0-9A-Za-z]{3}/; //regex that matches exactly 3 digits or letters
    var match = pattern.exec(filename); //attempts to find a match in the string

    if (match && match[0].length == 3) { //if there's a match and it's exactly three characters
        return match[0]; //return the matched code
    } else {
        return null; //return null if no valid three character code is found
    }
}
```

You can call this function with a filename like:

```javascript
var filename = "57-1Jn.usfm";
console.log(getThreeCharCode(filename));  // prints '1Jn'
```

Please note that the function assumes that the filename has exactly one three character code, which is the case with your example. If this isn't always true in your use-case, you might need to modify this function to return an array of all possible matches instead.
